  edibility: "psychoactive",
  toxicityNotes: "Psychoactive and toxic when consumed raw or undercooked. Active compounds (ibotenic acid and muscimol) cause a 'pantherine-muscaria' toxidrome: nausea, vomiting, ataxia, mydriasis, alternating CNS sedation and excitation, delirium, hallucinations, and rarely seizures or coma. Onset 30-90 minutes, peak ~3 hours, most cases resolve within 12-24 hours. Potency varies up to 10x (some sources cite up to 100x) between specimens, seasons, and varieties; spring/summer specimens reportedly contain ~10x the ibotenic acid/muscimol of autumn fruitings. Toxins concentrate in the cap cuticle and yellow subcuticular tissue. A. muscaria and A. pantherina together are a major cause of serious mushroom poisonings reported to Pacific Northwest poison control centers (Beug; Spoerke et al. 1994; Vo et al. 2018). Deaths are rare but documented, particularly with large doses (~15 caps), in children, or in cases complicated by aspiration during emesis or seizures. Parboiling in plentiful water (15+ min, water discarded) reduces but does not eliminate water-soluble toxins; drying or grilling can CONVERT ibotenic acid into the more potent muscimol rather than detoxifying. NOT recommended for casual foraging.",
