    medicinalUses: ["Historical/folk: topical liniments for joint pain in parts of Eastern Europe and Russia; insecticidal/fly-killing milk preparation (origin of the name 'fly agaric').", "Investigational: muscimol is a research tool in neuroscience for GABA-A receptor pharmacology and has been studied as a potential anxiolytic, anticonvulsant, and adjunct in functional neurosurgery; no approved clinical use.", "Current commercial: legal-gray-market gummies, tinctures, and microdose products marketed for mood, sleep, and 'lucid dreaming'; efficacy and safety not established and under increasing FDA/state regulatory scrutiny."],
    toxinsOfNote: ["Ibotenic acid - excitatory; causes nausea, vomiting, CNS excitation, neurotoxic to certain neurons at high doses", "Muscimol - inhibitory GABA-A agonist; sedation, ataxia, dysphoria, hallucinations, dream-like delirium, alternating with excitation", "Muscazone - minor photodegradation product; limited pharmacological activity", "Muscarine - present only in small amounts in A. muscaria (named for it historically but concentration too low to drive primary toxicity); causes peripheral cholinergic symptoms (SLUDGE) at high doses"],
    notes: "Toxin content is highly variable: 10x or more between specimens, with some reports of up to 100x variation between regions and seasons. Toxins concentrate in the red cap cuticle and yellow subcuticular tissue. Parboiling in copious water removes a substantial fraction of the water-soluble ibotenic acid and muscimol; drying converts ibotenic acid to the more potent muscimol and is the basis for traditional entheogenic preparations. A single fresh fruiting body (50-70 g) typically contains ~6 mg muscimol and up to ~70 mg ibotenic acid - sufficient to produce pronounced psychoactive effects in an adult."
