    itsClade: "Amanita subgenus Amanita, section Amanita, subsection Amanita; the A. muscaria species complex contains three deep ITS clades (Eurasian, Eurasian subalpine, and North American/Beringian) per Geml et al. 2006, with all three present in Alaska, supporting a Beringian center of diversification. PNW material falls almost entirely within the North American clade and is referable to A. muscaria subsp. flavivolvata sensu Tulloss.",
    keyPaper: "Geml, J., Laursen, G.A., O'Neill, K., Nusbaum, H.C. & Taylor, D.L. (2006). Beringian origins and cryptic speciation events in the fly agaric (Amanita muscaria). Molecular Ecology 15: 225-239.",
    notes: "Tulloss & Yang treat New World 'typical' red-with-yellow-warts populations as A. muscaria subsp. flavivolvata (Singer) Tulloss. Color forms (var. flavivolvata, var. guessowii/formosa, var. persicina, var. alba) do not all map cleanly to ITS clades; Geml et al. concluded that named varieties largely represent intraclade color polymorphisms rather than independent lineages."
