    consensus: "strong",
    disputeNotes: "Sources agree on morphology, ecology, taxonomy (with the var. flavivolvata vs. subsp. flavivolvata nomenclatural distinction), toxin profile, and ethnomycological significance. The only genuine dispute concerns edibility: Rubel & Arora (2008) and a minority of authors argue A. muscaria is a safe edible after thorough parboiling, while the FDA (2024), regional poison-control reviews (Vo et al. 2018; Beug), and the great majority of field guides and mycological societies treat it as a poisonous and psychoactive mushroom not recommended for casual consumption. We classify edibility as 'psychoactive' to capture both its toxicological status and its central place in entheogenic tradition."
