  edibility: "toxic",
  toxicityNotes: "TOXIC - contains the isoxazole neurotoxins ibotenic acid, muscimol, and muscazone (with trace muscarine), producing the so-called 'pantherina syndrome' (also called pantherina-muscaria syndrome or mycoatropine). Onset 30 minutes to 2-3 hours after ingestion. Symptoms include severe gastrointestinal distress (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea), dizziness, ataxia, muscle twitching and fasciculation, mydriasis, hot/flushed skin, alternating drowsiness and agitation, vivid illusions/hallucinations, delirium, deep sleep, and in heavier doses convulsions, seizures, and coma. A. pantherina/pantherinoides is regarded as MORE toxic on a per-gram basis than A. muscaria, with a higher muscimol:ibotenic-acid ratio that produces a higher rate of coma. Hospitalization is common; full recovery typically within 24-48 hours with supportive care (IV fluids, benzodiazepines for agitation/seizures, intubation if comatose). Fatalities are uncommon but documented, especially in young children, the elderly, and patients with cardiac disease. This is one of the most frequent causes of mushroom poisoning calls to the BC Drug and Poison Information Centre and to Oregon/Washington poison control. DO NOT consume; the toxins are heat-stable and not destroyed by cooking or drying."
