  edibility: "deadly",
  toxicityNotes: "Responsible for ~90% of all mushroom-related fatalities worldwide; a single cap can kill an adult. Contains three toxin classes: amatoxins (alpha-, beta-, gamma-amanitin), phallotoxins, and virotoxins. Alpha-amanitin is a bicyclic octapeptide that irreversibly inhibits eukaryotic RNA polymerase II, halting mRNA and protein synthesis and causing apoptosis. OATP1B3 transporters concentrate the toxin in hepatocytes, producing massive centrilobular hepatic necrosis; renal tubular necrosis also occurs. Toxins are NOT destroyed by cooking, drying, or freezing. Clinical course is biphasic: (1) 6-24 h asymptomatic latency, (2) 24-72 h severe GI phase (vomiting, cholera-like diarrhea, abdominal pain), (3) 48-96 h apparent recovery, (4) 3-7 d fulminant hepatic and renal failure. NO specific antidote exists; supportive care includes aggressive IV fluids, activated charcoal, intravenous silibinin (Legalon SIL), N-acetylcysteine (NAC), and liver transplant for severe cases. Mortality 10-50% even with modern care.",
  lookalikes: [
    { name: "Coccora (Fall coccora)", scientific: "Amanita calyptroderma", catalogId: "amanita-calyptroderma", danger: "edible-with-caution", keyFeatures: ["striate cap margin","cottony white veil patch","orange-brown cap","fishy odor"], distinguishingFeature: "Coccora has a strongly striate cap margin, thick cottony white universal-veil patch on cap, orange-brown to yellowish-brown cap, and fishy odor; A. phalloides lacks striations and the cottony cap patch and has a sweet odor. Frequently confused; foragers should NEVER consume any white-gilled Amanita unless extremely experienced." },
    { name: "Springtime amanita", scientific: "Amanita velosa", catalogId: "amanita-velosa", danger: "edible-with-caution", keyFeatures: ["striate cap margin","no ring","pinkish-tan to salmon cap"], distinguishingFeature: "A. velosa has a strongly striate cap margin, lacks a stem ring (annulus), and has a pinkish-tan to salmon cap; A. phalloides always has a persistent skirt-like annulus and a non-striate cap." },
    { name: "Western Caesar's amanita", scientific: "Amanita lanei", catalogId: "amanita-lanei", danger: "edible-with-caution", keyFeatures: ["orange-brown striate cap","thick white veil patch","yellow gill/stem tints"], distinguishingFeature: "A. lanei (= A. calyptroderma sensu lato by some authors) has an orange-brown striate cap with a thick white veil patch and bright yellow gills/stem tints; A. phalloides has white gills throughout and a non-striate olive-green to yellow cap." },
    { name: "Spring coccora", scientific: "Amanita vernicoccora", catalogId: "amanita-vernicoccora", danger: "edible-with-caution", keyFeatures: ["pale yellow to white cap","striate margin","cottony white veil patch","spring at elevation"], distinguishingFeature: "Pale yellow to nearly white cap with striate margin and cottony white universal-veil patch; spring fruiting at higher elevations. A. phalloides lacks striations and the cap patch." },
    { name: "Puffballs (button-stage confusion)", scientific: "Calvatia / Lycoperdon spp.", danger: "edible", keyFeatures: ["solid white inside","no cap/gills/stem when sliced"], distinguishingFeature: "True puffballs are solid white inside with NO trace of cap, gills, or stem when sliced vertically; young A. phalloides 'eggs' cut in half reveal the outline of a developing cap, gills, and stem inside the universal veil. Implicated in multiple BC poisonings." },
    { name: "Paddy straw mushroom", scientific: "Volvariella volvacea", catalogId: "volvariella-volvacea", danger: "edible", keyFeatures: ["pink spore print","pink mature gills","no ring"], distinguishingFeature: "Paddy straw has PINK spore print and pink gills at maturity, and no annulus (ring) on stem; A. phalloides has white spore print, white gills, and a prominent skirt-like ring. A common fatal confusion among Asian immigrant foragers." },
    { name: "Western destroying angel", scientific: "Amanita ocreata", catalogId: "amanita-ocreata", danger: "deadly", keyFeatures: ["pure white throughout","late winter to spring","under coast live oak"], distinguishingFeature: "A. ocreata is pure white throughout (no green/yellow tones), fruits late winter to spring under coast live oak; equally deadly via amatoxins." }
  ],
  culinary: { flavor: "Reported by survivors and historical accounts to be pleasant and delicious - this is part of what makes it so dangerous.", preparation: "DO NOT EAT. Toxins are heat-stable, water-soluble but not destroyed by cooking, drying, freezing, or any home preparation.", preservation: null },
  conservationNotes: "Invasive non-native species in North America (introduced from Europe ca. early 20th century, first California record ~1938). First documented invasive ectomycorrhizal fungus. Range is actively expanding northward along the Pacific coast; has jumped from ornamental host trees (cork oak, European chestnut) onto native coast live oak in California and native Garry oak in British Columbia (Berch et al. 2016; Pringle & Vellinga 2006). Reportable in some jurisdictions; do NOT spread fruit bodies, spores, or soil.",
