    notes: "Nephrotoxic non-protein amino acids cause acute tubulointerstitial nephritis and acute tubular necrosis with delayed onset (2-6 days for renal failure following 30 min - 12 h GI prodrome). Mechanism is incompletely understood but is distinct from the cyclopeptide amatoxin pathway (no hepatic necrosis dominant). Toxins are NOT destroyed by cooking. No amatoxins, phallotoxins, virotoxins, muscarine, ibotenic acid, or muscimol are reported in this species. Treatment is supportive: aggressive IV hydration, electrolyte and acid-base correction, and hemodialysis when indicated. Most patients recover normal renal function within several weeks of dialysis support, but fatalities and permanent renal impairment have been reported when dialysis is delayed or unavailable."
