  spores: { lengthMicrons: [6, 9], widthMicrons: [4, 6], shape: "ellipsoid", ornamentation: "smooth", reaction: "inamyloid; hyaline to faintly ochraceous in KOH", notes: "Reported ranges vary slightly by source: MushroomExpert gives 6-8.5 x 4-5 um, MykoWeb gives 7.5-9 x 5-6 um. Basidia 45-65 um long, typically 4-sterigmate. Spore deposit white (paler than the cream-yellow deposits of C. formosus and C. californicus)." },
  microhabitat: { slopeAspect: null, soilPh: [4.5, 6.0], soilTexture: "well-drained mineral soils overlain by deep conifer duff and moss layer", moisturePreference: "consistently moist but well-drained; thrives in mossy, humus-rich forest floor that does not pool water", indicatorPlants: ["Pseudotsuga menziesii", "Tsuga heterophylla", "Arbutus menziesii", "Gaultheria shallon", "Mahonia nervosa", "Polystichum munitum", "Hylocomium splendens", "Kindbergia oregana"], notes: "Strongly associated with mature to old-growth stands (Dunham et al. 2006 documented significantly higher occurrence in old-growth than in 40-60 year second-growth). Often fruits partially buried in deep duff on gentle to moderate slopes; soil pH inferred from typical PNW coniferous forest A-horizon values rather than from species-specific measurement." },
