  toxicityNotes: "DEADLY POISONOUS. Contains orellanine, one of the most potent nephrotoxins known in fungi. Poisoning is characterized by an extremely long asymptomatic latent period of 3 days to 3 weeks (mean ~8 days) after ingestion, followed by nonspecific gastrointestinal symptoms (nausea, vomiting, headache, myalgia, anorexia), intense thirst, polyuria/oliguria, flank pain, and progressive acute interstitial nephritis with tubular necrosis culminating in acute kidney injury. Orellanine generates oxygen free radicals while down-regulating antioxidant enzymes, is highly kidney-specific, and remains sequestered in renal tissue for months after ingestion. As little as 0.04 mg orellanine/kg body weight (2-3 mushrooms, ~30 g fresh) can cause lifelong dialysis-dependent renal failure. There is NO effective antidote; treatment is supportive (hemodialysis, hemoperfusion) and many survivors ultimately require kidney transplantation. The toxin is NOT degraded by cooking, freezing, or drying. The long latency means by the time symptoms appear, exposure may be forgotten or attributed to other causes - making history-taking and diagnosis difficult.",
