    notes: "Orellanine is structurally similar to the bipyridyl herbicides paraquat and diquat. It generates oxygen radicals while simultaneously down-regulating antioxidant defenses, is highly kidney-specific (concentrates in proximal renal tubular epithelium), inhibits protein synthesis and ATPase at the tubular brush border, and remains sequestered in renal tissue for months after ingestion. Toxin concentration varies by tissue (highest in cap and gills) and by individual fruiting body. NOT degraded by cooking, drying, or freezing. No specific antidote; treatment is supportive plus hemodialysis/hemoperfusion, with kidney transplantation often required for survivors."
