{
  id: "cyclocybe-aegerita",
  commonNames: ["Pioppino", "Black Poplar Mushroom", "Poplar Fieldcap", "Velvet Pioppini", "Tea Tree Mushroom", "Chestnut Mushroom", "Yanagi-matsutake"],
  scientific: "Cyclocybe aegerita",
  family: "Tubariaceae",
  order: "Agaricales",
  trophicMode: "saprotrophic",
  mycorrhizalPartners: [],
  hostTrees: [
    { common: "Black cottonwood", scientific: "Populus trichocarpa" },
    { common: "Other poplars", scientific: "Populus spp." },
    { common: "Willow", scientific: "Salix spp." },
    { common: "Alder", scientific: "Alnus rubra" },
    { common: "Elder", scientific: "Sambucus spp." },
    { common: "Fig (Mediterranean range)", scientific: "Ficus carica" },
    { common: "Elm", scientific: "Ulmus spp." }
  ],
  substrate: "Lignicolous; white-rot decomposer of dead and dying hardwood. Fruits in tufts on standing dead trunks, fallen logs, stumps, and exposed roots of broadleaf trees; also on hardwood mulch and woodchips in landscaped/urban settings.",
  habitat: "Riparian hardwood forests and floodplains; in the PNW chiefly on black cottonwood (Populus trichocarpa) and willow along rivers, sloughs, and wet bottomlands, less commonly on alder. Widespread and abundant in its native Mediterranean range; in the Pacific Northwest it is uncommon to local but genuinely present, with most occurrences in low-elevation riparian zones and on urban hardwood mulch.",
  elevationM: { min: 0, max: 600 },
  regionsPNW: ["Southwestern British Columbia (Lower Mainland riparian)", "Western Washington (Puget lowlands, lower Columbia)", "Western Oregon (Willamette Valley, lower Columbia, coastal river bottoms)", "Urban and landscaped areas throughout the PNW on hardwood mulch"],
  fruitingMonths: [4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11],
  peakMonths: [5, 6, 9, 10],
  conditions: {
    minRain7d: 15,
    idealDaysSinceRain: [3, 10],
    tempRangeC: [12, 24],
    humidityMinPct: 75
  },
  identification: {
    cap: "3-14 cm (most commonly 4-10 cm); hemispheric to convex when young, expanding to broadly convex or nearly plane in age; smooth, dry to subviscid, hygrophanous; dark chocolate-brown to deep reddish-brown at first, fading from the center outward to tan, beige, or cream with a darker disc; margin paler and often remains incurved; cuticle frequently cracking into a tessellated pattern in dry weather.",
    underside: "Gills adnate to slightly decurrent, close to crowded; pale cream to whitish when young, maturing through ochre to tobacco-brown or cinnamon-brown as spores ripen; edges entire.",
    stem: "5-15 cm long, 0.5-1.5 (-2) cm thick; cylindrical to slightly tapering toward a curved or rooting base; solid and fibrous; whitish to cream above the ring, becoming dingy ochre to brownish below; bearing a persistent, membranous superior ring that is white when young and becomes ochre-brown from falling spores; often arising in dense tufts from a common base attached to wood.",
    fleshColor: "White and firm in the cap, more fibrous in the stem; unchanging when cut.",
    sporePrintColor: "Dark brown to tobacco-brown",
    odor: "Pleasant, mild, slightly farinaceous to mealy-wine; taste mild, nutty, fruity-sweet and well regarded.",
    sizeCm: "Cap 3-14 cm; stem 5-15 x 0.5-2 cm"
  },
  edibility: "choice",
  toxicityNotes: "No toxins reported in C. aegerita itself; one of the most widely cultivated gourmet mushrooms in Europe and East Asia. The principal real-world risk is misidentification: tufted brown-spored mushrooms on wood overlap superficially with deadly Galerina marginata (which contains alpha-amanitin) and with hallucinogenic/inedible Pholiota and Cortinarius species. Wild collections should always be confirmed by spore print (tobacco-brown, not rusty-brown of Cortinarius and not the duller cinnamon-brown of Galerina), persistent membranous (not cortinate) ring, hardwood substrate, and absence of conifer association.",
  lookalikes: [
    {
      name: "Deadly galerina",
      scientific: "Galerina marginata",
      catalogId: "galerina-marginata",
      danger: "deadly",
      keyFeatures: ["small cap 1-4 cm","fragile ring","almost exclusively on conifer wood","rusty-brown spore print"],
      distinguishingFeature: "Much smaller (cap typically 1-4 cm vs. 3-14 cm), thinner-stemmed, with a fragile/evanescent ring that can disappear with handling; cap honey-brown and more strongly hygrophanous; grows almost exclusively on CONIFER wood and decorticated logs (occasionally on hardwood but predominantly conifer); spore print rusty-brown (not tobacco-brown); spores warty/rugulose under microscope. Contains alpha-amanitin at lethal concentrations - never assume a small brown tufted mushroom on wood is a pioppino."
    },
    {
      name: "Spring agrocybe / Spring fieldcap",
      scientific: "Agrocybe praecox",
      catalogId: "agrocybe-praecox",
      danger: "edible-with-caution",
      keyFeatures: ["small cap 3-7 cm","on ground or wood-chip mulch","tan-beige cap","spring fruiting"],
      distinguishingFeature: "Smaller (cap usually 3-7 cm, rarely to 9 cm); grows on the ground in grass, garden beds, or wood-chip mulch rather than directly out of dead hardwood trunks; fruits in spring; cap typically duller tan-beige and more uniform; lacks the dense caespitose tufts on wood characteristic of C. aegerita. Edible but variable in quality and reportedly causes GI upset in some individuals."
    },
    {
      name: "Golden scalycap / Scaly Pholiota",
      scientific: "Pholiota aurivella",
      catalogId: "pholiota-aurivella",
      danger: "edible-with-caution",
      keyFeatures: ["golden cap with dark scales","viscid cap","on hardwood","rusty-brown spore print"],
      distinguishingFeature: "Cap bright orange-yellow to golden with prominent dark appressed scales (not smooth); viscid cap surface; grows on hardwood (and sometimes conifer) but with conspicuous scales absent in C. aegerita. Spore print rusty-brown, not tobacco-brown."
    },
    {
      name: "Cortinarius species",
      scientific: "Cortinarius spp.",
      danger: "GI-upset",
      keyFeatures: ["cobwebby cortina no ring","rusty-brown spore print","mycorrhizal on ground"],
      distinguishingFeature: "Veil is cortinate (cobwebby fibers) and does not form a persistent membranous ring as in C. aegerita; spore print rusty-brown to ochre-brown (not tobacco-brown); mostly mycorrhizal on the ground under trees, not lignicolous in tufts on hardwood trunks. Several Cortinarius species (e.g., C. rubellus, C. orellanus) contain lethal orellanine."
    },
    {
      name: "Sheathed woodtuft",
      scientific: "Kuehneromyces mutabilis",
      catalogId: "kuehneromyces-mutabilis",
      danger: "edible-with-caution",
      keyFeatures: ["two-toned hygrophanous cap","scaly stem below ring","tufted on hardwood","small cap 2-6 cm"],
      distinguishingFeature: "Also tufted on hardwood with a ring, but cap is strongly two-toned hygrophanous (dark brown when wet, ochre when dry, often with a damp marginal zone); stem distinctly scaly below the ring; cap smaller (2-6 cm); easily confused with deadly Galerina marginata, so itself a risky choice for beginners."
    }
  ],
  culinary: {
    flavor: "Excellent: nutty, slightly sweet, fruity with a meaty, firm texture; one of the most highly regarded cultivated gourmet mushrooms in Italian and East Asian cuisines. Texture remains pleasantly al dente even after long cooking.",
    preparation: "Discard the lower tough portion of the stem; the upper stem and cap are both fully usable. Excellent sauteed with garlic and olive oil, in pasta and risotto, with eggs/frittata, in soups, braises, and stews. Pairs well with poultry, pork, and tomato-based sauces. Italian tradition pickles young, unopened buttons in oil (sott'olio).",
    preservation: "Keeps unusually well in the refrigerator (1-2 weeks); can be dried (texture and flavor concentrate nicely), sauteed and frozen, or preserved in olive oil after a vinegar blanch."
  },
  conservationNotes: "Not of conservation concern: widespread, abundant, and one of the most commercially cultivated mushrooms in the world (cha shu gu / tea tree mushroom production in China alone is in the hundreds of thousands of tonnes annually). In the PNW it is uncommon as a wild fruiting but its host trees (Populus, Salix) are abundant and the species is not at risk; wild populations may in fact be expanding via introductions from cultivation and via hardwood mulch in urban landscaping.",
  sources: [
    { name: "Wikipedia - Cyclocybe aegerita", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclocybe_aegerita" },
    { name: "First Nature - Cyclocybe cylindracea (Poplar Fieldcap)", url: "https://www.first-nature.com/fungi/cyclocybe-cylindracea.php" },
    { name: "Kuratani et al. 2024 - Cylindracin, a Cys-rich protein from Cyclocybe cylindracea (FEBS Open Bio, PMC11532979)", url: "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11532979/" },
    { name: "Ngai, Zhao & Ng 2005 - Agrocybin, an antifungal peptide from Agrocybe cylindracea (Peptides 26: 191-196)", url: "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15629530" },
    { name: "Vizzini, Angelini & Ercole 2014 - Le sezioni Velatae e Aporus di Agrocybe sottogenere Aporus; resurrection of genus Cyclocybe (Boll. Assoc. Micol. Ecol. Romana 92: 21-38)", url: "https://www.bamser.it/bollettino-amer" },
    { name: "MykoWeb - North American Species of Pholiota (Excluded: P. aegerita = Agrocybe aegerita)", url: "https://www.mykoweb.com/Pholiota/Excluded_Species.html" },
    { name: "Orban et al. 2021 - Transcriptome of fruiting stages in Cyclocybe aegerita (BMC Genomics 22)", url: "https://doi.org/10.1186/s12864-021-07648-5" },
    { name: "Zhang et al. 2020 - Agrocybe aegerita Serves as a Gateway for Identifying Sesquiterpene Biosynthetic Enzymes in Higher Fungi (ACS Chem. Biol.)", url: "https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acschembio.0c00155" },
    { name: "Grokipedia - Cyclocybe aegerita (taxonomy, phylogeny, identification synthesis)", url: "https://grokipedia.com/page/Cyclocybe_aegerita" },
    { name: "Stamets, P. - Growing Gourmet and Medicinal Mushrooms, 3rd ed. (Ten Speed Press, 2000), Agrocybe aegerita chapter", url: "https://fungi.com/" }
  ],

  spores: {
    lengthMicrons: [7, 11],
    widthMicrons: [5, 7],
    shape: "Ellipsoid to ovoid with a small but distinct germ pore",
    ornamentation: "Smooth, thick-walled, ochre-brown to tobacco-brown in deposit",
    reaction: "Dextrinoid wall (slightly reddish in Melzer's); not amyloid",
    notes: "Basidia 4-spored, clamped. Cheilocystidia abundant, lageniform to clavate-mucronate (a key microscopic feature). Pleurocystidia present in many collections. European C. aegerita has smaller spores (7-9 microns long) than Asian Cyclocybe chaxingu sensu stricto, a distinction used in multilocus phylogenies (Vizzini & Angelini 2014; Zhu et al. 2023)."
  },
  microhabitat: {
    slopeAspect: "No strong aspect preference; in PNW most often found on bottomland flats and low river-terrace flood zones, on shaded north- and east-facing exposures of standing dead trunks.",
    soilPh: [6.0, 7.5],
    soilTexture: "Substrate is wood, not soil; underlying riparian soils are typically alluvial sands, silts, and loams with high organic matter and consistent moisture.",
    moisturePreference: "Requires consistently moist (but not submerged) hardwood substrate; intolerant of prolonged drying. Riparian floodplain microclimate with high relative humidity is ideal.",
    indicatorPlants: ["Black cottonwood (Populus trichocarpa)", "Pacific willow (Salix lasiandra)", "Scouler's willow (Salix scouleriana)", "Red alder (Alnus rubra)", "Reed canary grass (Phalaris arundinacea) in adjacent understory", "Stinging nettle (Urtica dioica)"],
    notes: "Fruits caespitose (in dense tufts) from a single point on the host, often emerging from cracks in bark or from old wounds and pruning cuts; multiple flushes per season possible after rain. Urban occurrences on hardwood-chip mulch in landscaped beds are increasingly reported."
  },
  phenologyCues: [
    { cue: "Warm spring rains following a stretch of >15 C daytime temperatures", reliability: "strong" },
    { cue: "Fruiting 5-10 days after a soaking summer or early-fall rain event on cottonwood/willow snags", reliability: "strong" },
    { cue: "Night temperatures consistently above 10 C", reliability: "strong" },
    { cue: "Multiple flushes from the same trunk through the growing season as long as moisture persists", reliability: "moderate" },
    { cue: "Appearance on fresh hardwood mulch 4-8 weeks after application in landscaped beds", reliability: "moderate" },
    { cue: "Concurrent fruiting of Pleurotus populinus on the same cottonwood snags", reliability: "anecdotal" }
  ],
  bioactive: {
    compounds: ["Cylindracin (Cys-rich antifungal protein from fruiting bodies, Pri3 gene product; inhibits filamentous fungi, not yeasts or bacteria; Kuratani et al. 2024)", "Agrocybin (9 kDa antifungal peptide; also attenuates HIV-1 reverse transcriptase in vitro; Ngai et al. 2005)", "Beta-(1,3)/(1,6)-glucans (immunomodulatory polysaccharides typical of cultivated edible basidiomycetes)", "Aegeritin (antifungal protein from fruiting bodies)", "Indole alkaloids and sesquiterpenoids (including the unusual aroma compound 8,3'-cyclolignan-related volatiles, with C. aegerita serving as a model organism for fungal sesquiterpene synthase discovery; Zhang et al. 2020)", "Unspecific peroxygenase (UPO/AaeUPO, also called 'aromatic peroxygenase'); an enzyme of major biotechnological interest for selective hydroxylation/epoxidation chemistry", "Ergosterol and ergosterol peroxide", "Dietary fiber, B-vitamins, copper, potassium, selenium"],
    medicinalUses: ["Investigational antifungal applications based on cylindracin, agrocybin, and aegeritin", "Investigational immunomodulation via beta-glucans", "Reported in vitro antiproliferative / pro-apoptotic activity on several tumor cell lines (preliminary, not clinically established)", "Source organism for industrial biocatalysts (AaeUPO peroxygenase) used in pharmaceutical and fine-chemical synthesis"],
    toxinsOfNote: ["None reported in C. aegerita itself.", "WARNING: lookalike Galerina marginata contains lethal alpha-amanitin; any small tufted brown-spored mushroom on wood (especially on conifers) should be excluded before consuming."],
    notes: "One of the most thoroughly studied edible basidiomycetes from a biochemistry standpoint, partly because it has a well-characterized fruiting-body transcriptome (Orban et al. 2021) and a sequenced genome that has been mined extensively for sesquiterpene cyclases and oxidative enzymes."
  },
  dnaBarcode: {
    itsClade: "Family Tubariaceae (formerly placed in Strophariaceae and earlier in Bolbitiaceae); genus Cyclocybe Velen. (resurrected). Sister to Cyclocybe cylindracea (often treated as conspecific by European authors) and to the Asian C. chaxingu / C. salicacicola aggregate.",
    keyPaper: "Vizzini, A., Angelini, C. & Ercole, E. (2014). Le sezioni Velatae e Aporus di Agrocybe sottogenere Aporus: rivalutazione del genere Cyclocybe Velen. ed una nuova specie. Bollettino dell'Associazione Micologica ed Ecologica Romana 92: 21-38. Supplemented by Zhu, X.Y., Nyima, T., Vizzini, A., He, M.Q., Phurbu, D. & Zhao, R.L. (2023). Two new species of Cyclocybe (Agaricales, Tubariaceae) from China. Phytotaxa 620: 33-46.",
    notes: "Vizzini and co-authors used multilocus rDNA phylogenies (ITS + LSU + tef1-alpha) to demonstrate that the 'aegerita / cylindracea' clade is distinct from core Agrocybe sensu stricto and warrants resurrection of Velenovsky's genus Cyclocybe. The 2023 revisions added two Asian sister species. European populations are typically referred to as Cyclocybe aegerita (V. Brig.) Vizzini 2014, with Cyclocybe cylindracea (DC.) Vizzini & Angelini 2014 sometimes treated as conspecific."
  },
  verification: {
    sourcesAgreeing: 6,
    lastVerified: "2026-05-24",
    consensus: "strong",
    disputeNotes: "Sources agree on morphology, ecology, edibility (choice), cultivation status, and bioactive profile. The only persistent disagreement is nomenclatural: whether C. aegerita and C. cylindracea are one species or two. Most European and cultivation literature now uses the two as synonyms under C. aegerita (V. Brig.) Vizzini, while some databases retain C. cylindracea (DC.) Vizzini & Angelini as the preferred name; iNaturalist redirects C. aegerita to C. cylindracea. PNW occurrence is documented on cottonwood and willow but is far less common than in the Mediterranean range, and most PNW wild collections from urban mulch may represent introductions traceable to cultivation."
  }
}
,
{
  id: "floccularia-luteovirens",
  commonNames: ["Yellow Floccularia", "Saffron Parasol", "Golden Mushroom", "Grassland Yellow Mushroom", "Yellow Mushroom", "Huang Mogu"],
  scientific: "Floccularia luteovirens",
  family: "Agaricaceae",
  order: "Agaricales",
  trophicMode: "mycorrhizal",
  mycorrhizalPartners: ["Populus tremuloides", "Picea engelmannii", "Abies lasiocarpa", "Pinus contorta var. latifolia", "Pseudotsuga menziesii (occasional)"],
  hostTrees: [
    { common: "Quaking aspen", scientific: "Populus tremuloides" },
    { common: "Engelmann spruce", scientific: "Picea engelmannii" },
    { common: "Subalpine fir", scientific: "Abies lasiocarpa" },
    { common: "Lodgepole pine", scientific: "Pinus contorta var. latifolia" },
    { common: "Douglas-fir", scientific: "Pseudotsuga menziesii" }
  ],
  substrate: "Terrestrial in grassy/herbaceous soil under or at the margins of aspen groves and spruce-fir stands, and in adjoining subalpine and alpine meadows. Most PNW collections are from rich, deep, well-drained mountain meadow soils with a strong grass/forb cover; the mycelium associates with nearby tree roots even when fruitbodies emerge several meters out into open grassland. Note: in its much-better-studied Qinghai-Tibet Plateau range, it fruits in pure alpine meadow at 3200-4800 m and forms ectomycorrhizal associations primarily with Kobresia and other meadow plants; some authors therefore classify it as a meadow mycorrhizal species rather than a forest one. Genomic/phylogenomic work (Xing et al. 2021; Liu et al. 2020) confirms an ectomycorrhizal lifestyle, contradicting older treatments that called it saprotrophic.",
  habitat: "In western North America a montane to subalpine species of the Rocky Mountains, Intermountain West, and east-slope Cascades. In the PNW the great majority of collections come from east of the Cascade crest in the high-elevation aspen parklands and spruce-fir/subalpine meadow mosaics of the Wallowas, Blue Mountains, Ochocos, eastern Cascades (Deschutes/Fremont-Winema/Okanogan-Wenatchee NFs), and the Okanagan highlands of BC; rare to absent on the wet, low-elevation west side. Fruits scattered, gregariously, or in fairy rings in grassy openings, along aspen-grove edges, and out into open subalpine meadows; favors stable, mature meadow systems and is most abundant in cool summers following heavy late-summer monsoonal/thunderstorm rains. Strikingly visible from a distance as a bright golden-yellow shaggy mushroom standing 10-20 cm above the grass.",
  elevationM: { min: 1500, max: 3500 },
  regionsPNW: ["Eastern Cascades (Okanogan-Wenatchee NF, Fremont-Winema NF, Deschutes NF)", "Wallowa Mountains", "Blue Mountains (NE Oregon / SE Washington)", "Ochoco Mountains", "Okanagan Highlands (BC interior)", "Kettle Range / Selkirks (NE Washington)", "East-slope subalpine meadows (Mount Adams / Goat Rocks eastern aspect)", "Steens Mountain (high elevations)"],
  fruitingMonths: [7, 8, 9],
  peakMonths: [8, 9],
  conditions: {
    minRain7d: 15,
    idealDaysSinceRain: [5, 12],
    tempRangeC: [4, 18],
    humidityMinPct: 65
  },
  identification: {
    cap: "5-13 cm broad; convex when young, expanding to plano-convex and finally nearly flat in age; dry; ground color whitish to pale yellow but almost entirely covered by bright golden-yellow to chrome-yellow, appressed-fibrillose to slightly raised scales (most conspicuous on the disc and toward the margin), the whitish ground only becoming visible in old specimens; cap margin shaggy with yellow partial-veil remnants hanging off the edge",
    underside: "Gills attached to the stem, usually by a notch (sinuate-adnexed); close to crowded with frequent short-gills; pale yellow to greenish-yellow, often with finely jagged/eroded edges; covered when very young by a thick yellow partial veil",
    stem: "5-12 cm long x 1.5-3.5 cm thick; equal or slightly enlarged toward the base; white and smooth/bald above a prominent shaggy double ring; sheathed below the ring with conspicuous shaggy yellow scales over a whitish ground (matching the cap); basal mycelium white and prominent, often binding soil and grass roots",
    fleshColor: "White throughout; firm when young and fresh; unchanging on exposure (does not bruise yellow, red, or brown)",
    sporePrintColor: "White",
    odor: "Mild and pleasantly mushroomy; not distinctive; not farinaceous, not spicy. Taste mild to faintly sweet/nutty.",
    sizeCm: "Cap 5-13 cm; stem 5-12 cm x 1.5-3.5 cm; medium-large, robust, Tricholoma-like in stature"
  },
  edibility: "edible",
  toxicityNotes: "Long-established edible in Asia (the famed 'Huang Mogu' / Yellow Mushroom of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, harvested commercially and studied for medicinal/antitumor compounds) and historically consumed in Europe. North American collections are eaten by some foragers but reports of mild GI upset exist, possibly from confusion with other shaggy yellow agarics or from individual sensitivity; cook thoroughly and try a small portion first. Not recommended for beginners because of confusion with potentially toxic yellow Cortinarius species and immature yellow Amanita.",
  lookalikes: [
    { name: "Death Cap (yellow forms) / Yellow-yellow Amanita group", scientific: "Amanita gemmata / Amanita aprica / Amanita pantherinoides", catalogId: "amanita-gemmata", danger: "toxic", keyFeatures: ["free gills","basal volva or bulb","warts wash off","white spore print non-amyloid"], distinguishingFeature: "Yellow to ochre Amanitas in PNW conifer/mixed forests can be superficially similar from above. Differences: FREE gills (vs. attached/sinuate in Floccularia), a true basal volva/cup or bulb with patches (vs. fibrillose sheath and basal mycelium pad), warts on the cap (not appressed yellow fibrillose scales) that wash off, white spore print (same) but spores NON-amyloid (vs. amyloid in Floccularia). Contains ibotenic acid/muscimol (or for Amanita phalloides yellow forms, amatoxins - deadly)." },
    { name: "Deadly Webcaps (yellow forms)", scientific: "Cortinarius rubellus / Cortinarius orellanus group", catalogId: "cortinarius-rubellus", danger: "deadly", keyFeatures: ["rusty-brown spore print","cobwebby cortina","rusty-brown mature gills","orellanine"], distinguishingFeature: "Some yellow-brown Cortinarius species cause fatal kidney failure (orellanine). Differences: RUSTY-BROWN spore print (vs. white in Floccularia), cobwebby cortina (not a shaggy membranous double ring), gills rusty-brown at maturity (not pale yellow), no shaggy yellow scales sheathing the stem." },
    { name: "Honey Mushroom", scientific: "Armillaria ostoyae / A. solidipes", catalogId: "armillaria-ostoyae", danger: "edible-when-cooked", keyFeatures: ["honey-brown cap","dark tuft-like scales","clusters at conifer base","on wood"], distinguishingFeature: "Also has a ring and grows in groups, but cap is honey-brown to tawny (not bright golden-yellow), scales are dark and tuft-like (not yellow fibrillose), gills white-cream becoming pinkish-stained, grows in clusters at the base of conifers or from buried wood (not in open meadows), and is parasitic/saprotrophic on wood rather than mycorrhizal in grassland" },
    { name: "Shaggy Parasol", scientific: "Chlorophyllum olivieri / C. brunneum", catalogId: "chlorophyllum-olivieri", danger: "edible-with-caution", keyFeatures: ["whitish-grey cap with brown scales","free gills","flesh stains reddish","disturbed soils"], distinguishingFeature: "Also has shaggy scaly cap and ring, but ground color whitish-grey/tan with brown scales (not yellow), FREE gills, flesh stains reddish then brown when cut, taller and more slender, common in disturbed soils/gardens at lower elevations" },
    { name: "Gypsy Mushroom", scientific: "Cortinarius caperatus", catalogId: "cortinarius-caperatus", danger: "edible", keyFeatures: ["wrinkled-radial cap","rusty-brown spore print","cobwebby cortina"], distinguishingFeature: "Also has a yellowish ring and can be ochre-yellow, but cap is wrinkled-radial (not shaggy-scaly), RUSTY-BROWN spore print, cobwebby cortina rather than a double membranous ring, no yellow scales sheathing the stem" },
    { name: "Yellow Knight / Man on Horseback", scientific: "Tricholoma equestre (= T. flavovirens)", catalogId: "tricholoma-equestre", danger: "edible-with-caution", keyFeatures: ["smooth bright yellow cap","no ring","white spores","sandy pine forests"], distinguishingFeature: "Also bright yellow with a Tricholoma stature and white spores; but cap is smooth to finely fibrillose (NOT shaggy-scaly), NO ring, NO sheathing yellow scales on stem, occurs in sandy conifer (pine) forests rather than subalpine meadows. Implicated in rhabdomyolysis poisonings in Europe - no longer recommended for the table." }
  ],
  culinary: {
    flavor: "Mild, pleasantly mushroomy, slightly sweet/nutty when fresh; not strongly flavored. In Tibetan and Qinghai cuisine it is highly prized for its delicate flavor, firm texture, and brilliant yellow color, which it retains on cooking. Considered a premium wild mushroom in China and exported dried.",
    preparation: "Clean by brushing or wiping; remove any grass and soil from the shaggy stem base. Slice and saute in butter or neutral oil; works well in soups, stir-fries, rice dishes, and dumplings (a traditional Tibetan preparation is in butter-tea broth or steamed momos). Always cook thoroughly - do not eat raw. Try a small portion the first time as North American foragers occasionally report mild GI upset.",
    preservation: "Dries very well, retaining bright yellow color and concentrating flavor (this is the standard commercial preservation method on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau); reconstitute in warm water 20-30 minutes before use. Can also be sliced and frozen after a brief saute. Not commonly pickled."
  },
  conservationNotes: "Globally not formally listed but considered a slow-growing, habitat-specific species. In its main range on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, populations are under heavy harvest pressure (a major income source for local herders) and have shown declines, prompting genomic conservation studies. In the PNW it is uncommon and patchily distributed, restricted to mature subalpine aspen/meadow ecosystems east of the Cascades; populations are vulnerable to grazing intensification, meadow conversion, aspen decline, and climate-driven loss of snowpack/summer moisture in subalpine meadows. Best practice: photograph for records, harvest sparingly, leave the shaggy base and surrounding mycelial pad intact, and do not rake or disturb the meadow turf.",
  sources: [
    { name: "MushroomExpert.Com - Floccularia luteovirens (Kuo 2020)", url: "https://www.mushroomexpert.com/floccularia_luteovirens.html" },
    { name: "Burke Herbarium Image Collection (University of Washington) - Floccularia luteovirens", url: "http://biology.burke.washington.edu/herbarium/imagecollection/taxon.php?Taxon=Floccularia+luteovirens" },
    { name: "GBIF Backbone Taxonomy - Floccularia luteovirens (Alb. & Schwein.) Pouzar", url: "https://www.gbif.org/species/3333955" },
    { name: "Liu et al. (2020) Draft Genome Assembly of Floccularia luteovirens, an Edible and Symbiotic Mushroom on Qinghai-Tibet Plateau (PMC)", url: "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7144084/" },
    { name: "Xing et al. (2021) Genomic and Transcriptomic Analyses of Floccularia luteovirens (PMC)", url: "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8618933/" },
    { name: "Research Status and Prospects of Floccularia luteovirens (2023, PMC)", url: "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10672661/" }
  ],
  spores: { lengthMicrons: [5, 7.5], widthMicrons: [4, 5.5], shape: "ellipsoid to broadly ellipsoid", ornamentation: "smooth, thin-walled, hyaline, no germ pore", reaction: "amyloid in Melzer's reagent", notes: "Average ~6.4 x 4.6 microns (Q = 1.25-1.63, Qav ~1.39). Basidia clavate, 24-32 x 8-9.5 microns, predominantly 2-spored (occasionally 4-spored). Cheilocystidia broadly clavate; pleurocystidia lageniform with digitiform apex. Clamp connections abundant in all tissues. Spore data per Diversity and Multigene Phylogeny of Floccularia (MDPI J. Fungi 2025)." },
  microhabitat: { slopeAspect: "Variable but tends to favor gentle to moderate slopes with northern, eastern, or level aspects retaining late-summer soil moisture; in the PNW often on benches, swales, and gentle east/north-facing meadow margins where snowmelt and monsoonal moisture persist", soilPh: [5.5, 7.5], soilTexture: "Deep, well-drained, organic-rich loam to silt-loam meadow soils with strong root mat; tolerates moderately rocky/gravelly mountain soils on volcanic or glacial parent material", moisturePreference: "Mesic; requires consistent late-summer soil moisture from monsoonal rains or persistent snowmelt; not found in droughty exposed sites or saturated bogs", indicatorPlants: ["Populus tremuloides (quaking aspen)", "Picea engelmannii", "Abies lasiocarpa", "Festuca idahoensis (Idaho fescue)", "Carex spp. (meadow sedges)", "Kobresia spp. (on Qinghai-Tibet Plateau analog meadows)", "Lupinus argenteus", "Achillea millefolium", "Geum triflorum"], notes: "Strongly associated with mature, ungrazed-to-lightly-grazed subalpine aspen-meadow ecotones; fairy rings often develop in stable Festuca/Carex meadow turf adjacent to aspen clones. Heavy livestock grazing, soil compaction, or meadow plowing eliminates fruiting." },
  phenologyCues: [
    { cue: "Cumulative late-July through August monsoonal rainfall exceeding ~25-40 mm over a 7-10 day window after a warm spell", reliability: "strong" },
    { cue: "Nighttime soil temperatures at 5 cm dropping into the 6-12 C range following summer thunderstorm pulses", reliability: "strong" },
    { cue: "Visible flush of mushroom activity in nearby aspen groves (e.g., Leccinum, Suillus, Russula) ~1-2 weeks before Floccularia emerges in adjacent meadows", reliability: "moderate" },
    { cue: "Peak bloom of late-summer meadow forbs (Achillea, Geum triflorum seed heads, Solidago) coincides with main fruiting window", reliability: "moderate" },
    { cue: "Anecdotal: Tibetan herder tradition links fruiting to the first heavy rains following the warmest week of summer on the plateau (translatable cue for PNW subalpine sites)", reliability: "anecdotal" }
  ],
  bioactive: { compounds: ["Floccularia luteovirens polysaccharides (FLP, beta-glucan-rich heteropolysaccharides)", "ergosterol and ergosterol peroxide", "free amino acids (notably glutamic acid, alanine) contributing to umami flavor", "selenium and zinc (elevated trace minerals from plateau soils)", "phenolic antioxidants", "mannitol and trehalose"], medicinalUses: ["Immunomodulation and antitumor activity (polysaccharide fractions tested against sarcoma S180, hepatoma H22, and HeLa cell lines in Chinese pharmacological studies)", "Antioxidant / free-radical scavenging (used in functional foods and nutraceutical research in China)", "Traditional Tibetan and Qinghai use as a tonic food for general vitality and post-illness recovery", "Hypoglycemic and hypolipidemic effects reported in rodent models", "Hepatoprotective activity demonstrated for crude extracts"], toxinsOfNote: [], notes: "No known toxins of clinical concern; occasional mild GI upset reported in North American foragers is not linked to a characterized toxin and may reflect misidentification or individual sensitivity. Not a hyperaccumulator of heavy metals in published surveys, though selenium content is naturally elevated. Bioactivity research reviewed in Research Status and Prospects of Floccularia luteovirens (PMC 2023)." },
  dnaBarcode: { itsClade: "Floccularia luteovirens clade s.str. within genus Floccularia (Agaricaceae); ITS analyses (Cao et al. 2025, J. Fungi) resolve four well-supported clades in the genus - F. luteovirens (MLB 81%, BPP 1.00), F. asiatica, F. sinensis, and F. flava - with Western North American collections historically called F. albolanaripes / F. fusca / F. pitkinensis forming a separate intermixed clade sister to true F. luteovirens. PNW material long passed as F. luteovirens likely represents the F. albolanaripes complex; molecularly confirmed F. luteovirens s.str. in North America is largely restricted to Rocky Mountain / Intermountain subalpine sites.", keyPaper: "Cao et al. (2025) Diversity and Multigene Phylogeny of the Genus Floccularia (Agaricales, Basidiomycota), Journal of Fungi 11(1):74 (MDPI); supported by Liu et al. (2020) G3 and Xing et al. (2021) draft genome / phylogenomic placement of Floccularia within Agaricales (Agaricaceae), not within the Armillaria (Physalacriaceae) complex despite the old Armillaria straminea synonymy.", notes: "Historic name Armillaria straminea P. Kumm. is a synonym; the genus was erected by Pouzar (1957) precisely to remove this species from Armillaria. Phylogenomic placement firmly within Agaricaceae near Agaricus, NOT within the Armillaria/Physalacriaceae clade. ITS is sufficient for species-level identification within Floccularia; multilocus (ITS + nrLSU + tef1 + rpb2) recommended for fine-scale clade resolution." },
  verification: { sourcesAgreeing: 6, lastVerified: "2026-05-23", consensus: "strong", disputeNotes: "Taxonomic dispute: a 2025 multigene phylogeny (Cao et al., J. Fungi) indicates that most Western North American collections labeled 'F. luteovirens' actually belong to the F. albolanaripes complex, with true F. luteovirens s.str. confirmed mainly from Asia, Europe, and the Rocky Mountains. PNW field records should be treated as the F. luteovirens species complex pending sequence confirmation. Trophic mode also historically disputed (saprotrophic vs. mycorrhizal) but resolved as ectomycorrhizal by Liu et al. 2020 and Xing et al. 2021 genomic evidence." }
}
