    notes: "Galerina marginata was the first non-Amanita mushroom in which ribosomal biosynthesis of amanitin from a short precursor peptide (MSDIN family) was demonstrated (Hallen, Luo, Scott-Craig & Walton 2007; Luo et al. 2012). The toxins act by binding RNA polymerase II with sub-nanomolar affinity, halting transcription and triggering hepatocyte apoptosis. Toxins are heat-stable and survive all normal food preparation."
