  habitat: "A specialist mycoparasite that taps into the ectomycorrhizal Hartig net of Suillus species (and possibly closely related Rhizopogon) growing on conifer roots, rather than forming a true mutualistic ectomycorrhiza with the tree itself. Olsson et al. (2000) demonstrated for the related G. roseus / Suillus bovinus / Pinus sylvestris system that Gomphidius hyphae penetrate and parasitize the Suillus mantle, drawing carbon ultimately derived from the tree via the Suillus partner; G. glutinosus is understood to function analogously, exploiting Suillus partners of spruce (and other conifers) such as members of the Suillus / Rhizopogon clade associated with Picea, Tsuga, Pseudotsuga, and Abies. Found in mature mossy conifer forests, plantations, and along trails and road edges; in the PNW especially common in north-coast Sitka spruce forests and in interior Engelmann spruce / subalpine fir stands. Solitary, scattered, or in small troops, fruiting after sustained autumn rains.",
