  dnaBarcode: {
    itsClade: "Gomphidius glutinosus s.s. forms a well-supported clade within Gomphidiaceae (Boletales, suborder Suillineae), sister to other Gomphidius species (G. roseus, G. subroseus, G. oregonensis, G. maculatus). Molecular work confirms Gomphidiaceae and Suillaceae as sister families consistent with the mycoparasitism hypothesis.",
    keyPaper: "Olsson, P.A., Munzenberger, B., Mahmood, S. & Erland, S. (2000). Molecular and anatomical evidence for a three-way association between Pinus sylvestris and the ectomycorrhizal fungi Suillus bovinus and Gomphidius roseus. Mycological Research 104(11): 1372-1378. doi:10.1017/S0953756200002823. (Type study demonstrating Gomphidius mycoparasitism on Suillus; G. glutinosus is interpreted analogously.) Also Miller 2003 on Gomphidiaceae systematics.",
    notes: "ITS sequences from PNW collections match European G. glutinosus closely; no cryptic-species splits formally proposed for PNW material, though G. oregonensis (smaller spores, clustered habit) is sometimes mistakenly reported as G. glutinosus and is genetically distinct."
  },
  verification: {
    sourcesAgreeing: 8,
    lastVerified: "2026-05-23",
    consensus: "strong",
    disputeNotes: "Strong consensus on morphology, edibility, and host range. The mycoparasitism interpretation (Gomphidius parasitizing Suillus rather than forming a direct ectomycorrhiza with the tree) is supported by Olsson et al. 2000 for G. roseus on Suillus bovinus and is widely extended to G. glutinosus; some older references and field guides still describe G. glutinosus as 'mycorrhizal with spruce' without acknowledging the Suillus intermediary, so trophic classification is sometimes inconsistently reported as 'mycorrhizal' vs. 'parasitic/mixed'. The specific Suillus partner(s) of G. glutinosus in PNW spruce forests have not been definitively identified at the species level and warrant further molecular work."
  }
