  bioactive: { compounds: ["Hericenones (fruiting body, presumed shared with genus)", "Erinacines (mycelial cyathane diterpenoids, presumed shared with genus)", "Ergosterol", "Beta-glucans", "Ergothioneine"], medicinalUses: ["Promoted commercially as a nootropic and nerve-growth-factor (NGF) stimulator alongside H. erinaceus", "Traditional immunomodulatory and digestive tonic uses (genus-level, Chinese and Japanese folk medicine)", "Investigated for neuroprotective and cognition-supporting activity (genus-level evidence; species-specific clinical data lacking)"], toxinsOfNote: [], notes: "Most NGF-induction and neurotrophic literature is on H. erinaceus; H. abietis is assumed to share the cyathane diterpenoid/hericenone chemistry of the genus but species-specific bioactive profiling is limited. No known toxins; rare allergic reactions reported." },
  dnaBarcode: { itsClade: "Hericium core clade (sister to H. erinaceus; closely related to H. americanum and H. coralloides; distinct from H. alpestre/H. laciniatum subclade)", keyPaper: "Hallenberg, Nitare & Larsson (2013) 'Species complexes in Hericium' and Park et al. (2004) ITS rDNA phylogeny of Hericium (analyzing H. abietis, H. alpestre, H. americanum, H. coralloides, H. erinaceus, H. laciniatum)", notes: "ITS rDNA used as the standard fungal barcode; PCR-based molecular markers developed for rapid Hericium species ID. African (H. ophelieae, H. bembedjaense) and Asian lineages form separate clades." },
