    medicinalUses: ["No accepted medicinal use. Some fasciculol derivatives are studied as calmodulin inhibitors and as lead compounds for anti-inflammatory or anti-tumor chemistry, but the intact mushroom is toxic and not used therapeutically."],
    toxinsOfNote: ["Fasciculol E - principal toxic steroid, LD50 (i.p., mice) approximately 50 mg/kg, calmodulin inhibitor", "Fasciculol F - LD50 (i.p., mice) approximately 168 mg/kg", "Fasciculic acids - additional bitter calmodulin-inhibiting triterpenoids", "Naematolin - bitter principle contributing to the diagnostic taste"],
    notes: "The clinical picture is dominated by delayed-onset (5-10 h) severe gastroenteritis. Renal involvement (proteinuria, acute kidney injury) has been documented in larger-dose cases. A single literature-reported fatality showed hepatic, renal, and myocardial injury, but the patient had consumed a mixed-species dish so attribution to H. fasciculare alone is uncertain. Because the toxins are calmodulin inhibitors, symptoms may not respond to standard supportive care as quickly as a simple irritant gastroenteritis would."
