    toxinsOfNote: [],
    notes: "No toxins are documented in H. lactifluorum itself, and no human poisonings have been recorded in centuries of consumption. Laperriere et al. (2018, Genome 61:329-336) showed that as infection progresses the host's DNA is largely replaced by H. lactifluorum DNA and the metabolite profile is profoundly altered - including neutralization of the acrid/peppery latex compounds of Lactifluus piperatus-group hosts, which is why parasitized fruitbodies become palatable. The bright orange surface pigment is a reliable chemical marker (KOH -> dark purple) and produces a strong natural dye."
