  substrate: "Brown heart-rot wood-decay fungus on large, old, living conifers; begins as a tree parasite (infecting heartwood through wounds, broken tops, and large branch stubs) and continues as a saprotroph after the host dies and becomes a snag. Causes a brown cubical rot with characteristic thick white mycelial felts in cracks. Strictly a conifer specialist; in the PNW most often on Douglas-fir, western larch, and hemlocks, with rare occurrences on spruce, true fir, and ponderosa pine. Perennial conks can persist on the same host for many decades.",
  habitat: "Old-growth coniferous forests of the Northern Hemisphere (Eurasia, Morocco, and western North America). In the PNW it is now largely restricted to remnant old-growth and structurally complex mature stands of Douglas-fir, western larch, and hemlock in Washington, Oregon, British Columbia, and southeast Alaska, with scattered occurrences inland on Larix occidentalis in the Inland Empire (eastern Washington, northern Idaho, western Montana). Conks typically hang high (up to ~20 m) on the trunks or large limbs of veteran/legacy trees with broken tops or fire scars. Strongly associated with mature forest structure (large diameter, decadent, fire-scarred or top-killed trees) and is essentially absent from second-growth and managed plantations. Fruitbodies are perennial and persist for decades, releasing spores during warm months.",
