  dnaBarcode: { itsClade: "Elata clade (black morels), phylogenetic species Mel-10 sensu O'Donnell et al. 2011 / Kuo et al. 2012", keyPaper: "Kuo M, Dewsbury DR, O'Donnell K, Carter MC, Rehner SA, Moore JD, Moncalvo J-M, Canfield SA, Stephenson SL, Methven AS, Volk TJ (2012) Taxonomic revision of true morels (Morchella) in Canada and the United States. Mycologia 104(5):1159-1177. doi:10.3852/11-375", notes: "Formally described in 2012 from a King County, WA type collection; previously circulated as phylogenetic species Mel-10 and lumped with M. angusticeps / M. brunnea as the 'Classic North American Black Morel'. Multi-locus phylogeny (ITS, LSU, EF1-alpha, RPB1, RPB2) places it firmly in the Elata clade; ITS sequences distinguish it from the morphologically similar forest-dwelling M. brunnea and M. snyderi. Sister relationships within the Elata clade further refined by Richard et al. 2015 and Taskin et al. 2012." },
  verification: { sourcesAgreeing: 6, lastVerified: "2026-05-23", consensus: "strong", disputeNotes: "Strong consensus on taxonomy, morphology, ecology, and edibility across Kuo/MushroomExpert, MykoWeb, Burke Herbarium, Wikipedia, and the primary Kuo et al. 2012 protologue. The only genuinely disputed/unresolved area is the etiology of the rare morel neurological syndrome - no causative toxin has been chemically identified, and the hydrazine hypothesis remains speculative and unconfirmed for Morchella spp." }
