  edibility: "deadly",
  toxicityNotes: "Historically eaten in many parts of Europe (especially Eastern Europe) and once listed as edible after cooking. RECLASSIFIED as deadly poisonous after the death of German mycologist Julius Schaffer in 1944, who developed vomiting, fever, and renal failure ~1 hour after a meal and died 17 days later. Causes 'Paxillus syndrome': an as-yet-uncharacterized antigen in the mushroom binds covalently to the surface of red blood cells; the immune system produces IgG antibodies against this antigen-RBC complex. After repeated meals (often over months or years), a subsequent ingestion triggers massive immune-mediated (Type II hypersensitivity) intravascular hemolysis. Onset is 1-2 hours post-ingestion with vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and hypotension, followed within hours by hemoglobinuria, jaundice, acute kidney injury, disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), shock, acute respiratory failure, and potentially death. Reaction is UNPREDICTABLE - a person may eat the mushroom for years with no symptoms and then suffer a fatal episode. There is NO SAFE PREPARATION - cooking, drying, parboiling, and pickling all DO NOT destroy the antigen. There is no antidote; treatment is supportive (plasmapheresis, transfusion, dialysis). Officially classified as dangerously poisonous by German, French, Swiss, and North American mycological authorities.",
