    medicinalUses: [],
    toxinsOfNote: ["Paxillus antigen (immune-mediated): an unidentified antigenic component (likely a glycoprotein) that binds covalently to the surface of erythrocytes and induces production of specific IgG antibodies; on re-exposure, antibody-antigen-RBC complexes activate complement and trigger massive intravascular hemolysis (Type II hypersensitivity).", "Heat-labile gastrointestinal irritants causing acute vomiting/diarrhea when consumed raw or undercooked (a separate, less severe syndrome).", "Muscarine has been reported in trace amounts but is not considered clinically significant.", "Involutin and related compounds generate reactive oxygen species via Fenton chemistry in the gut and may contribute to oxidative damage."],
    notes: "The Paxillus syndrome is mechanistically distinct from amatoxin, orellanine, gyromitrin, or muscarine poisoning - it is an acquired immunological reaction, not a direct chemical toxicity. This means symptom-free consumption history provides ZERO protection; in fact, repeated exposure INCREASES risk by building circulating IgG titer. No clinical antidote exists; treatment is supportive (plasmapheresis, transfusion, hemodialysis, corticosteroids)."
