  dnaBarcode: {
    itsClade: "Order Boletales, family Paxillaceae, genus Paxillus. ITS phylogeny reveals Paxillus involutus sensu lato is a species complex of at least four reproductively isolated lineages (PS I-IV per Hedh et al. 2008): PS I = P. obscurosporus, PS II = P. involutus sensu stricto, PS III = P. validus, PS IV = undescribed; Jargeat et al. 2014 added P. cuprinus as a fifth lineage previously misapplied as P. involutus. North American material includes P. involutus s.s. and the closely related P. vernalis (aspen/birch associate) and P. rubicundulus (alder associate).",
    keyPaper: "Jargeat, P., Chaumeton, J.-P., Navaud, O., Vizzini, A. & Gryta, H. (2014). The Paxillus involutus (Boletales, Paxillaceae) complex in Europe: Genetic diversity and morphological description of the new species Paxillus cuprinus, typification of P. involutus s.s., and synthesis of species boundaries. Fungal Biology 118(1): 12-31.",
    notes: "Hedh, Samson, Erland & Tunlid (2008, Mycological Research 112: 965-975) first established four phylogenetic species using five protein-coding loci (hydA, actA, rabA, gpiA, beta-tubulin); Jargeat et al. (2014) confirmed and extended this with ITS, tef1-alpha, and gpd, formally describing P. cuprinus. Toxicity (Paxillus syndrome) appears to be shared across the entire complex - all members should be considered deadly until proven otherwise."
  },
  verification: {
    sourcesAgreeing: 12,
    lastVerified: "2026-05-23",
    consensus: "strong",
    disputeNotes: "All consulted sources (MykoWeb, MushroomExpert.com, Wikipedia, First Nature, Woodland Trust, Stover et al. 2019, ScienceDirect Human Toxicology, Jargeat et al. 2014, Hedh et al. 2008, Olesen 1991, German/French/Swiss mycological authorities) agree on morphology, ecology, taxonomy, and deadly toxicity via immune-mediated hemolysis (Paxillus syndrome). Historical European folk consumption is acknowledged but uniformly condemned by all modern authorities. The only ongoing scientific dispute is the precise molecular identity of the antigen, which remains uncharacterized as of 2019-2024 toxicology literature. Edibility classification 'deadly' is unambiguous and universal in current literature."
  }
