  toxicityNotes: "Historically reported as a 'good edible' in older Japanese, European, and North American field guides (including the PNW Key Council 2003 trial key). This recommendation is now obsolete. In autumn 2004 across nine prefectures of Japan (centered on Niigata, Yamagata, Akita), 59 people developed acute encephalopathy after eating sugihiratake (Pleurocybella porrigens); 17 died (death 13-29 days after symptom onset, symptoms appearing up to 3 weeks after ingestion). A second fatal case occurred in 2009 in a 65-year-old hemodialysis patient. Almost all victims had pre-existing chronic kidney disease (many on hemodialysis), and the mean age was ~70. The Japanese government and most modern Western field guides now classify the species as poisonous / deadly and explicitly recommend against consumption by anyone, regardless of renal status, because the toxin(s) and dose-response are incompletely characterized and apparently healthy individuals have also been sickened.",
