  bioactive: { compounds: ["beta-glucans (pleuran-type immunomodulatory polysaccharides)", "ergothioneine", "ergosterol and ergosterol peroxide", "lovastatin (mevinolin) at low concentrations typical of Pleurotus", "laccases and manganese peroxidases (lignin-degrading enzymes)", "phenolic antioxidants"], medicinalUses: ["Traditional and modern use as a general nutritive and immunomodulatory food mushroom", "Investigated for cholesterol-lowering (statin-mediated) effects shared across the genus Pleurotus", "Source of dietary ergothioneine, an antioxidant amino acid", "Studied for mycoremediation of hydrocarbon- and lignin-rich waste streams"], toxinsOfNote: [], notes: "No species-specific medicinal compounds beyond the well-characterized Pleurotus suite have been isolated from P. populinus; most bioactivity data are extrapolated from the closely related P. ostreatus complex. Rare hypersensitivity pneumonitis ('mushroom worker's lung') is documented in commercial Pleurotus cultivators exposed to heavy spore loads." },
  dnaBarcode: { itsClade: "Pleurotus ostreatus species complex, Intersterility Group III (ISG III); sister to the P. ostreatus / P. pulmonarius Northern Hemisphere clade, resolved as a distinct terminal lineage in nrITS and IGS1 phylogenies.", keyPaper: "Vilgalys R. & Sun B.L. (1994). Ancient and recent patterns of geographic speciation in the oyster mushroom Pleurotus revealed by phylogenetic analysis of ribosomal DNA sequences. PNAS 91(10): 4599-4603. See also Vilgalys et al. (1993) Can. J. Bot. 71:113-128 (intersterility groups) and Petersen & Hughes treatments of ISG III; later integrated in Li et al. (2020) IMA Fungus 11:10 on the P. ostreatus complex.", notes: "Cross-mating tests (Vilgalys et al. 1993) demonstrated complete intersterility between ISG III (P. populinus) and the P. ostreatus / P. pulmonarius groups, supporting biological species status independently corroborated by rDNA phylogenies." },
